{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781082892924,"sessionID":"ses_14f307519ffe9pcxGOYtQjmgt2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_01BMPrUKUWJcEaCMtPNAPiFR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-color-advanced/instruction.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-color-advanced/instruction.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Rust `ls` — Color, Filtering & Flag Combinations\n2: \n3: ## Task\n4: \n5: Build an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that reproduces GNU coreutils `ls`\n6: **colorized output, ignore/hide filtering, SELinux context, and multi-flag\n7: combinations**. Your implementation must be a standalone binary located at\n8: `/app/workspace/rls`. It will be invoked as:\n9: \n10: ```\n11: /app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n12: ```\n13: \n14: For the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\n15: output as GNU `ls`. This is the **advanced/integration** tier: cases combine\n16: color with long format, recursion, classification, and sorting, so a fairly\n17: complete `ls` is needed — but the focus is on **color output, ignore/hide\n18: filtering, SELinux context, and correct flag interaction**.\n19: \n20: ## Required Flags\n21: \n22: ### Color\n23: \n24: | Flag | Description |\n25: |------|-------------|\n26: | `--color[=WHEN]` | `always`/`auto`/`never` — colorize using `LS_COLORS` |\n27: \n28: When `--color=always` is set, wrap each name in the ANSI escape derived from\n29: `LS_COLORS` based on file type / permission bits. The test environment uses:\n30: \n31: ```\n32: LS_COLORS=\"rs=0:di=01;34:ln=01;36:mh=00:pi=40;33:so=01;35:do=01;35:bd=40;33;01:cd=40;33;01:or=40;31;01:mi=00:su=37;41:sg=30;43:ca=00:tw=30;42:ow=34;42:st=37;44:ex=01;32\"\n33: ```\n34: \n35: ### Filtering\n36: \n37: | Flag | Description |\n38: |------|-------------|\n39: | `-B`, `--ignore-backups` | Ignore entries ending with `~` |\n40: | `-I PATTERN`, `--ignore=PATTERN` | Ignore entries matching the shell glob PATTERN |\n41: | `--hide=PATTERN` | Like `-I` but overridden by `-a`/`-A` |\n42: \n43: ### Context\n44: \n45: | Flag | Description |\n46: |------|-------------|\n47: | `-Z`, `--context` | Print SELinux context (display `?` when unavailable) |\n48: \n49: ### Combinations exercised\n50: \n51: The suite also runs bundled flags such as `-laSr`, `-latr`, `-lhS`, `-RlF`,\n52: `-lisg`, and override pairs like `-fl`, `-l -1`, `-C -l`, `-1 -C`. Your flag\n53: parser must honor GNU's **last-one-wins** override semantics among conflicting\n54: format/sort flags, plus the side effects of `-f` (enables `-a`, disables `-l`\n55: and color).\n56: \n57: ## Environment Variables\n58: \n59: | Variable | Usage |\n60: |----------|-------|\n61: | `LC_ALL` | Always set to `C` — affects sort order |\n62: | `LS_COLORS` | Color codes for `--color=always` (value above) |\n63: | `COLUMNS` | Output width (set to `80`) |\n64: | `TZ` | Timezone (`UTC`) |\n65: | `TERM` | Terminal type (`xterm-256color`) |\n66: \n67: ## Output Behavior\n68: \n69: - **Color**: emit `\\033[<code>m<name>\\033[0m` (with the `rs=0` reset) using the\n70:   `LS_COLORS` entry matching the file's type (`di`, `ln`, `pi`, `so`, `bd`,\n71:   `cd`, `ex`, `or` for broken links, special perms `su`/`sg`/`tw`/`ow`/`st`,\n72:   …). `--color=never`/`auto` (non-tty) produce no escapes.\n73: - **Ignore/hide**: `-B` drops `*~`; `-I`/`--hide` drop glob matches; `-a`/`-A`\n74:   override `--hide` but not `-I`.\n75: - **`-Z`**: print the context column (`?` in this environment) in the\n76:   appropriate position.\n77: - **Combinations**: apply all bundled flags together; resolve conflicts by the\n78:   last occurrence on the command line.\n79: - **Exit code**: 0 on success, non-zero on error.\n80: \n81: ## Output Fidelity\n82: \n83: Reproduce GNU `ls` output for every flag and combination above. The ANSI color\n84: escapes in particular must be byte-for-byte identical, not merely visually\n85: similar. Favor broad correctness across color, ignore/hide filtering, context,\n86: and flag interaction over perfecting any single case.\n87: \n88: ## Time Limit\n89: \n90: You have **2 hours** (7200 seconds). Because this tier integrates many features,\n91: build a solid long/sorted listing first, then add `LS_COLORS` parsing and the\n92: filters, then verify the flag-override edge cases. When ~10 minutes remain, run a\n93: final `cargo build --release`, copy the binary to `/app/workspace/rls`, and make\n94: sure it runs without crashing.\n95: \n96: ## Constraints\n97: \n98: - You must implement this in **Rust**.\n99: - You may **not** use the `uutils` crate or any crate that provides a\n100:   ready-made `ls` implementation.\n101: - You may use standard library crates and general-purpose crates (e.g. `libc`,\n102:   `nix`, `clap`, `regex`).\n103: - Your final binary must be at `/app/workspace/rls`.\n104: - The system `ls` command is disabled — do not attempt to call it.\n105: - Each test has a per-case timeout (10 seconds).\n106: \n107: ## Getting Started\n108: \n109: Example fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in\n110: `/app/fixtures/` and test definitions in `/app/tests/`.\n111: \n112: ## Tips\n113: \n114: - Parse `LS_COLORS` into a map; resolve a file's key by type first, then special\n115:   bits (setuid `su`, setgid `sg`, sticky+other-writable `tw`, other-writable\n116:   `ow`, sticky `st`), then by extension (`*.ext`) for regular files, falling\n117:   back to `ex` for executables.\n118: - A broken symlink uses `or` (orphan); a valid symlink uses `ln` (or its target\n119:   color if `ln=target`).\n120: - `-I` uses `fnmatch`-style globbing against the entry name; `--hide` is the\n121:   same but suppressed when `-a`/`-A` is present.\n122: - Implement flag parsing so the **last** of a conflicting set wins; `-f` has the\n123:   documented side effects (enable `-a`, disable sorting, `-l`, and color).\n\n(End of file - total 123 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Rust `ls` — Color, Filtering & Flag Combinations\n\n## Task\n\nBuild an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that reproduces GNU coreutils `ls`\n**colorized output, ignore/hide filtering, SELinux context, and multi-flag\ncombinations**. Your implementation must be a standalone binary located at\n`/app/workspace/rls`. It will be invoked as:\n\n```\n/app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n```\n\nFor the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\noutput as GNU `ls`. This is the **advanced/integration** tier: cases combine\ncolor with long format, recursion, classification, and sorting, so a fairly\ncomplete `ls` is needed — but the focus is on **color output, ignore/hide\nfiltering, SELinux context, and correct flag interaction**.\n\n## Required Flags","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-color-advanced/instruction.md","text":"# Rust `ls` — Color, Filtering & Flag Combinations\n\n## Task\n\nBuild an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that reproduces GNU coreutils `ls`\n**colorized output, ignore/hide filtering, SELinux context, and multi-flag\ncombinations**. Your implementation must be a standalone binary located at\n`/app/workspace/rls`. It will be invoked as:\n\n```\n/app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n```\n\nFor the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\noutput as GNU `ls`. This is the **advanced/integration** tier: cases combine\ncolor with long format, recursion, classification, and sorting, so a fairly\ncomplete `ls` is needed — but the focus is on **color output, ignore/hide\nfiltering, SELinux context, and correct flag interaction**.\n\n## Required Flags\n\n### Color\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--color[=WHEN]` | `always`/`auto`/`never` — colorize using `LS_COLORS` |\n\nWhen `--color=always` is set, wrap each name in the ANSI escape derived from\n`LS_COLORS` based on file type / permission bits. The test environment uses:\n\n```\nLS_COLORS=\"rs=0:di=01;34:ln=01;36:mh=00:pi=40;33:so=01;35:do=01;35:bd=40;33;01:cd=40;33;01:or=40;31;01:mi=00:su=37;41:sg=30;43:ca=00:tw=30;42:ow=34;42:st=37;44:ex=01;32\"\n```\n\n### Filtering\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `-B`, `--ignore-backups` | Ignore entries ending with `~` |\n| `-I PATTERN`, `--ignore=PATTERN` | Ignore entries matching the shell glob PATTERN |\n| `--hide=PATTERN` | Like `-I` but overridden by `-a`/`-A` |\n\n### Context\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `-Z`, `--context` | Print SELinux context (display `?` when unavailable) |\n\n### Combinations exercised\n\nThe suite also runs bundled flags such as `-laSr`, `-latr`, `-lhS`, `-RlF`,\n`-lisg`, and override pairs like `-fl`, `-l -1`, `-C -l`, `-1 -C`. Your flag\nparser must honor GNU's **last-one-wins** override semantics among conflicting\nformat/sort flags, plus the side effects of `-f` (enables `-a`, disables `-l`\nand color).\n\n## Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Usage |\n|----------|-------|\n| `LC_ALL` | Always set to `C` — affects sort order |\n| `LS_COLORS` | Color codes for `--color=always` (value above) |\n| `COLUMNS` | Output width (set to `80`) |\n| `TZ` | Timezone (`UTC`) |\n| `TERM` | Terminal type (`xterm-256color`) |\n\n## Output Behavior\n\n- **Color**: emit `\\033[<code>m<name>\\033[0m` (with the `rs=0` reset) using the\n  `LS_COLORS` entry matching the file's type (`di`, `ln`, `pi`, `so`, `bd`,\n  `cd`, `ex`, `or` for broken links, special perms `su`/`sg`/`tw`/`ow`/`st`,\n  …). `--color=never`/`auto` (non-tty) produce no escapes.\n- **Ignore/hide**: `-B` drops `*~`; `-I`/`--hide` drop glob matches; `-a`/`-A`\n  override `--hide` but not `-I`.\n- **`-Z`**: print the context column (`?` in this environment) in the\n  appropriate position.\n- **Combinations**: apply all bundled flags together; resolve conflicts by the\n  last occurrence on the command line.\n- **Exit code**: 0 on success, non-zero on error.\n\n## Output Fidelity\n\nReproduce GNU `ls` output for every flag and combination above. The ANSI color\nescapes in particular must be byte-for-byte identical, not merely visually\nsimilar. Favor broad correctness across color, ignore/hide filtering, context,\nand flag interaction over perfecting any single case.\n\n## Time Limit\n\nYou have **2 hours** (7200 seconds). Because this tier integrates many features,\nbuild a solid long/sorted listing first, then add `LS_COLORS` parsing and the\nfilters, then verify the flag-override edge cases. When ~10 minutes remain, run a\nfinal `cargo build --release`, copy the binary to `/app/workspace/rls`, and make\nsure it runs without crashing.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- You must implement this in **Rust**.\n- You may **not** use the `uutils` crate or any crate that provides a\n  ready-made `ls` implementation.\n- You may use standard library crates and general-purpose crates (e.g. `libc`,\n  `nix`, `clap`, `regex`).\n- Your final binary must be at `/app/workspace/rls`.\n- The system `ls` command is disabled — do not attempt to call it.\n- Each test has a per-case timeout (10 seconds).\n\n## Getting Started\n\nExample fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in\n`/app/fixtures/` and test definitions in `/app/tests/`.\n\n## Tips\n\n- Parse `LS_COLORS` into a map; resolve a file's key by type first, then special\n  bits (setuid `su`, setgid `sg`, sticky+other-writable `tw`, other-writable\n  `ow`, sticky `st`), then by extension (`*.ext`) for regular files, falling\n  back to `ex` for executables.\n- A broken symlink uses `or` (orphan); a valid symlink uses `ln` (or its target\n  color if `ln=target`).\n- `-I` uses `fnmatch`-style globbing against the entry name; `--hide` is the\n  same but suppressed when `-a`/`-A` is present.\n- Implement flag parsing so the **last** of a conflicting set wins; `-f` has the\n  documented side effects (enable `-a`, disable sorting, `-l`, and color).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":123,"totalLines":123,"truncated":false}},"title":"rust-ls-color-advanced/instruction.md","time":{"start":1781082892899,"end":1781082892919}},"metadata":{"anthropic":{"caller":{"type":"direct"}}},"id":"prt_eb0d026820013Q0K9TQW0pw3LB","sessionID":"ses_14f307519ffe9pcxGOYtQjmgt2","messageID":"msg_eb0cfa4fb001jZ4yrc9wD1aQPb"}}
